> etc.?
> 
> Note that all the above are fine in the US, and it is at least arguable  
that
> some have both technical superiority over the vanilla PGP Grady is  
promoting
> and a much larger user base.
> 
> Even Clipper seems much more cryptographically robust, but I leave it  
off
> the above list because of the key escrow, which appalls some.
> 
> Grady and his colleagues are having trouble not because of some  
"superior"
> system the government would like to suppress, but because unlike the  
above
> systems, they decided to make their own rules using personal logic  
instead
> of checking on and following the existing rules as others have done.
> 
> It is also a fair assumption that some of Grady's messages here were the
> equivalent of waving a red flag in front of a bull--and we must assume  
the
> readership of these newsgroups is uh, er, quite wide.
> 
> All in all, it seems to me (one man's opinion) that this is becoming a
> wonderful illustration of the principle that sometimes being "right" is  
the
> enemy of achieving one's objectives.
> 
> If the second subpoena mentioned by Grady is indeed as represented, this  
is
> VERY serious business, because his associates are asked to appear in  
front
> of a Grand Jury. This is not a simple inquiry, but the first step in a
> prosecution. If the Grand Jury indicts, the matter can be extremely  
costly
> and painful, and it would be hard, given the circumstances of the  
particular
> case, and the many others (see the above list) who HAVE obeyed the rules  
and
> aren't being prosecuted, for a civil liberties organization (IMHO) to  
see
> its way clear to ponying up the money for a defense. This may end up not  
a
> test of constitutional principles, but of the government's right to make
> reasonable rules. I would be surprised if such a case can be won against
> that right. But what do I know--I'm not an attorney.
> 
> Given the history of previous discussion in this group, let me suggest  
that
> those with contrary opinions to mine ought to be able to express them
